    <question>
        <prompt>The KKK's revival in the 1920s expanded to target:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Only African Americans</option>
            <option letter="b">Catholics, Jews, immigrants, and African Americans</option>
            <option letter="c">Political reformers</option>
            <option letter="d">Business leaders</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The KKK's 1920s revival expanded its targets beyond African Americans to include Catholics, Jews, immigrants, and others perceived as threatening "traditional" American values. This broader focus reflected post-WWI nativism and cultural anxieties. The organization gained millions of members nationwide and significant political influence before declining due to internal scandals and public opposition.</explanation>
    </question>
